\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear Sampling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common practice when performing integration between two points in the atmosphere is to subdivide rays by a fixed number of steps.
 However,
 the very large variation in the ray length leads to widely varying step sizes.
 This may cause integration to skip over regions of the atmosphere where the gradient of the density functions is the highest.
 This problem is especially noticible for rays which pass through the relatively thin Mie scattering layer.
 When rendering,
 this problem is manifested by banding artifacts in the scattering and transmittance textures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Power Mapping Sampling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to address the banding artifacts,
 we will instead sample the ray at heights defined by the power mapping function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=u^{p_{u}}\cdot H_{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the parameters defined:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=\frac{x}{width-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in\left(0,width-1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm for sampling a ray at heights defined by the power mapping function is as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Precompute the sample heights of the weight power mapping function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Discard zero length rays (e.g.
 scattering is 0.0 and transmittance is 1.0)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Always sample the ray at the endpoints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the ray intersects the planet then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sample the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P_{a},P_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 with decreasing heights
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Else if 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\phi\right)\geq0$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sample the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P_{a},P_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 with increasing heights
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Otherwise subdivide the ray at the tangent point 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{T}$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sample the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P_{a},P_{T}\right)$
\end_inset

 with decreasing heights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sample the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P_{T},P_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 with increasing heights
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
To compute the tangent point 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{T}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=-\frac{dot\left(P_{a},\left(P_{b}-P_{a}\right)\right)}{dot\left(\left(P_{b}-P_{a}\right),\left(P_{b}-P_{a}\right)\right)}\in\left(0,1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{T}=P_{a}+t\cdot\left(P_{b}-P_{a}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the next sampling point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 for a sample height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\frac{h-h_{a}}{h_{b}-h_{a}}\in\left(0,1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\left(x_{a}+s\cdot\left(x_{b}-x_{a}\right),y_{a}+s\cdot\left(y_{b}-y_{a}\right),z_{a}+s\cdot\left(z_{b}-z_{a}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The power mapping sampling procedure should be applied to ray integration for transmittance and atmospheric scattering computations.
\end_layout

